<p><strong>Pinyon Mouse (<em>Peromyscus truei)</em></strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Cricetidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Peromyscus truei</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Pinyon Mouse<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Pinyon Mouse has a length of 3⅗- 4 inches, a tail length of 3⅖-4⅘ inches, and a weight of 19-31 grams. It is a large-eared mouse (nearly 1 inch high), with a grayish brown color. Its tail can either be slightly longer or slightly shorter than its body. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=pinyon%20mouse&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This mouse resides in rocky terrains with scattered pinyon pines and junipers. It bears 3-6 young once or more times a year. It breeds principally in spring and summer. It is a good climber and feeds mainly on seeds and nuts. It lays its nests in trees and among rocks. Coyotes and Gray Foxes are common predators.<br />
